===Etymology===
Commonly claimed to have come from:
* {{w|King James Version of the Bible}}, ''{{w|Book of Proverbs}}'', [[s:Bible (King James)/Proverbs#Chapter 13|13:24]]
*: “He that spareth his rod hateth his son: but he that loveth him chasteneth him betimes.”

Due to the associated “spoil" concept which is not in the Bible, it more likely came from:

* a 17th century poem by {{w|Samuel Butler}} called ''{{w|spare the rod and spoil the child|Hudibras}}''. In the poem, a love affair is likened to a child, and {{l|en|spank|spanking}} is mockingly commended as a way to make the love grow stronger. The actual verse reads:<ref>[http://gracethrufaith.com/selah/spare-the-rod-and-spoil-the-child/]</ref>
*: “What medicine else can cure the fits<br />
*: Of lovers when they lose their wits?<br />
*: Love is a boy by poets styled<br />
*: Then spare the rod and spoil the child.”

